e then the two are linked to each other. At first, Geralt did not take her because women cannot become witchers. However, fate caused Geralt and Ciri to cross their paths thrice, with him claiming her for a second time when he invokes the Law of Surprise on a traveling merchant he saves from monsters during a random encounter; and after the death of her grandmother, Queen Calanthe of Cintra, Geralt ends up taking the girl into his care, training and loving her as his own daughter. \n\nFollowing the short stories, the novels unfold as Geralt is pulled into a whirlwind of events in his attempts to protect Ciri from those who would do her harm, becoming reluctantly embroiled in the political contentions of monarchs and emperors.\n\n==Literary analysis and reception ==\nGeralt is described as being emblematic of Polish popular culture's spirit of \"[[neo-liberal]] anti-politics\" in the 1990s.<ref name=\"Apor2008\">{{cite book|last=Apor|first=P\u00e9ter|title=Past for the eyes: East European representations of communism in cinema and museums after 1989|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SO8LAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=28 May 2011|year=2008|publisher=Central European University Press|isbn=9789639776050|page=198}}</ref> He is a professional, carrying out his duties and unwilling to become involved in the \"petty quarrels\" of the contemporary politics.<ref name=\"Apor2008\"/> [[Marek Oramus]] compared Geralt to [[Raymond Chandler]]'s signature character [[Philip Marlowe]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Oramus |first=Marek |author-link=Marek Oramus |date=2 September 2000 |title=Only the right image of a witcher |trans-title=Jedynie s\u0142uszny wizerunek wied\u017amina |url=https://archiwum.polityka.pl/art/jedynie-sluszny-wizerunek-wiedzmina,365834.html |language=Polish |work=[[Polityka]] |location=[[Poland]] |access-date=30 May 2011 |pages=52\u201354}}</ref> In 2018, [[GamesRadar]] ranked him as the 6th best hero in video game history.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamesradar.com/heroes-in-video-games/3/ |title=The best heroes in video games |last= |first= |date=28 February 2018 |website=[[GamesRadar+]] |publisher=[[Future plc|Future Publishing]] |access-date=31 October 2018 |quote=}}</ref> In 2018, Geralt was included in [[Tom's Guide]] Top 25 Best Video Game Characters of All Time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tomsguide.com/us/pictures-story/1544-best-video-game-characters-of-all-time.html|title=The 25 Best Video Game Characters of All Time|last=July 2018|first=Tom's Guide Staff 07|website=Tom's Guide|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==In other media==\n=== Film ===\n[[Micha\u0142 \u017bebrowski]] portrays Geralt in the Polish-language adaptation movie ''[[The Hexer (film)|The Hexer]]''.\n\n===Television===\n* [[Micha\u0142 \u017bebrowski]] portrays Geralt in the polish adaptation series ''[[The Hexer (TV series)|The Hexer]]''.\n* [[Henry Cavill]] portrays Geralt in the [[Netflix]] [[The Witcher (TV series)|adaptation of the books]], the first season of which was released in 2019.<ref name=\"directors\">{{cite web | url=https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/netflixs-the-witcher-casts-pivotal-roles-of-ciri-yennefer | title=Netflix\u2019S The Witcher casts pivotal roles of Ciri & Yennefer | date=10 October 2018 | publisher=Netflix | accessdate=16 January 2019 }}</ref> Sapkowski served as a creative consultant on the project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/witcher-saga-tv-series-adaptation-ordered-at-netflix-1004558|title='The Witcher' Saga TV Series Adaptation Ordered at Netflix|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Geralt of Rivia.png|thumb|Geralt as he appears in ''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]'' (2015)]] -->[[File:W3 SS Geralt.png|thumb|208x208px|Geralt in ''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]'']]\nGeralt's adventures continues in a non-canonical version by CD Projekt Red's video game trilogy (''[[The Witcher (video game)|The Witcher]]'', ''[[The Witcher 2: Assassins of Kings]]'' and ''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]''), where he is still alive after being killed by a mob during an anti non-human riot at the end of the Witcher novel saga and his body was taken in a boat by his daughter Ciri to [[Avalon]].\n\nSapkowski stated that the games are a work of art of their own and that they cannot be considered either an \"alternative version\", or a sequel, \"because this can only be told by Geralt's creator. A certain Andrzej Sapkowski.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-11-06-ever-wondered-what-the-author-of-the-witcher-books-thinks-about-the-games|title=Ever wondered what the author of The Witcher books thinks about the games?|last=Purchese|first=Robert|date=7 November 2012|work=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nGeralt, voiced by [[Doug Cockle]], appeared as a guest character in the 2018 game ''[[Soulcalibur VI]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.cdprojektred.com/news/play-as-geralt-of-rivia-in-soulcalibur-vi/ |title=Play as Geralt of Rivia in SOULCALIBUR VI! |last= |first= |date=15 March 2018 |website=[[CD Projekt|CD Projekt Red]] |publisher=[[CD Projekt]] |access-date=19 March 2018 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nGeralt also appeared in special content for ''[[Monster Hunter: World]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2019/02/08/monster-hunter-world-the-witcher-ciri-geralt/|title=Monster Hunter World x The Witcher contracts earn you Geralt and Ciri armor and weapon sets|last=Nunneley|first=Stephany|date=February 8, 2019|work=[[VG247]]|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref> and ''[[Daemon X Machina]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dualshockers.com/daemon-x-machina-witcher-3-geralt-ciri-dlc/|title=Daemon X Machina Meets The Witcher 3 With New Geralt and Ciri DLC|date=2019-12-05|website=DualShockers|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Novels}}\n*[[Reynevan]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Witcher series}}\n{{Soul series}}\n\n[[Category:The Witcher]]\n[[Category:Characters in fantasy novel series]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video game characters]]\n[[Category:Fantasy film characters]]\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1986]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who use magic]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with accelerated healing]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with albinism]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with superhuman strength]]\n[[Category:Fictional knights]]\n[[Category:Fictional mutants]]\n[[Category:Fictional monster hunters]]\n[[Category:Fictional swordsmen]]\n[[Category:Soulcalibur series guest characters]]\n", "name_user": "142.197.226.197", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Corrected the name)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geralt_of_Rivia"}
{"title_page": "Chersomanes", "text_new": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| image = Chersomanes albofasciata (Etosha).jpg\n| image_caption = [[Spike-heeled lark]] (''Chersomanes albofasciata'')\n| taxon = Chersomanes\n| authority = [[Jean Cabanis|Cabanis]], 1851\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = 2, see text\n| range_map = Chersomanes distribution map.png\n| range_map_caption = {{legend0|#008000|range of genus|outline=gray}} \n}}\n\n'''''Chersomanes''''' is a genus of [[lark]]s in the family [[Alaudidae]] found in southern and southeastern Africa.\n\nIt contains the two species:<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2018 | title=Nicators, reedling, larks | work=World Bird List Version 8.2 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/larks/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Image !! Scientific name !! Common Name !! Distribution\n|-\n|[[File:Beesley's Lark, Beesley's (Chersomanes beesleyi) 3 (46575626381).jpg|120px]] || ''Chersomanes beesleyi'' || [[Beesley's lark]] ||  northeastern Tanzania\n|-\n|[[File:Spike-heeled lark 2018 03 10 13 20 38 3271.jpg|120px]] || ''Chersomanes albofasciata''|| [[Spike-heeled lark]] ||  southern Africa\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q10746093}}\n\n[[Category:Chersomanes| ]]\n[[Category:Bird genera]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Alaudidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| image = Chersomanes albofasciata (Etosha).jpg\n| image_caption = [[Spike-heeled lark]] (''Chersomanes albofasciata'')\n| taxon = Chersomanes\n| authority = [[Jean Cabanis|Cabanis]], 1851\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = 2, see text\n| range_map = Chersomanes distribution map.png\n| range_map_caption = {{legend0|#008000|range of genus|outline=gray}} \n}}\n\n'''''Chersomanes''''' is a genus of [[lark]]s in the [[Alaudidae]] family found in southern and south-eastern Africa.\n\nIt contains the two species:<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2018 | title=Nicators, reedling, larks | work=World Bird List Version 8.2 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/larks/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Image !! Scientific name !! Common Name !! Distribution\n|-\n|[[File:Beesley's Lark, Beesley's (Chersomanes beesleyi) 3 (46575626381).jpg|120px]] || ''Chersomanes beesleyi'' || [[Beesley's lark]] ||  north-eastern Tanzania\n|-\n|[[File:Spike-heeled lark 2018 03 10 13 20 38 3271.jpg|120px]] || ''Chersomanes albofasciata''|| [[Spike-heeled lark]] ||  southern Africa\n|-\n|}\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q10746093}}\n\n[[Category:Chersomanes| ]]\n[[Category:Bird genera]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Alaudidae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chersomanes"}
{"title_page": "Mirafra", "text_new": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| image = Bengal bushlark (Mirafra assamica) in Kolkata W IMG 4596.jpg\n| image_caption =  [[Bengal bush lark]] (''Mirafra assamica'')<br/>in [[Kolkata]] ([[West Bengal]], India) \n| taxon = Mirafra\n| authority = [[Thomas Horsfield|Horsfield]], 1821\n| diversity_link = #Species list in taxonomic order\n| diversity = 24 species <small>(but see text)</small>\n| synonyms = * ''Geocoraphus''\n* ''Megalophonus''\n* ''Spilocorydon''\n| range_map = Mirafra distribution map.png\n| range_map_caption = {{legend0|#008000|global range of genus|outline=gray}}<ref name = map>Based on maps in the Handbook of the Birds of the World and the BirdLife Datazone</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Mirafra''''' is a genus of [[lark]] in the family [[Alaudidae]]. Some ''Mirafra'' species are called \"larks\", while others are called \"bush larks\". They are found from Africa through South Asia to Australia.\n\n==Taxonomy and systematics==\nThe phylogeny of larks (Alaudidae) was reviewed by Alstr\u00f6m et al. (2013) who found that the following species form a well supported monophyletic group, which is the sister lineage to [[Heteromirafra]].<ref name=\"Alstr\u00f6m et al. (2013)\">{{cite journal|last1=Alstr\u00f6m|first1=Per|last2=Barnes|first2=Keith N.|last3=Olsson|first3=Urban|last4=Barker|first4=F. Keith|last5=Bloomer|first5=Paulette|last6=Khan|first6=Aleem Ahmed|last7=Qureshi|first7=Masood Ahmed|last8=Guillaumet|first8=Alban|last9=Crochet|first9=Pierre-Andre|last10=Ryan|first10=Peter G.|title=Multilocus phylogeny of the avian family Alaudidae (larks) reveals complex morphological evolution, non-monophyletic genera and hidden species diversity|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|date=2013|volume=69|issue=3|pages=1043\u20131056|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2013.06.005|pmid=23792153|url=https://pub.epsilon.slu.se/11222/2/alstrom_fig_1.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Extant species===\nThe genus contains twenty-four species:<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2018 | title=Nicators, reedling, larks | work=World Bird List Version 8.2 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/larks/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Image !! Scientific name !! Common Name !! Distribution\n|-\n| [[File:Eastern clapper lark (Mirafra fasciolata subsp fasciolata), crop.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra fasciolata''|| [[Eastern clapper lark]]   || southern Africa in Zambia, Namibia, Botswana, Lesotho and South Africa.\n|-\n| [[File:Mirafra apiata -Namaqua National Park, South Africa-8 Cropped.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra apiata'' || [[Cape clapper lark]]  || southern Africa\n|-\n| [[File:Red-winged Lark.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra hypermetra'' || [[Red-winged lark]]   || Ethiopia, Kenya, Somalia, South Sudan, Tanzania and Uganda\n|-\n| [[File:Mirafra africana2.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra africana'' || [[Rufous-naped lark]]  ||  sub-Saharan Africa\n|-\n| [[File:Flappet Lark, Sakania, DR Congo (16025285505), crop.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra rufocinnamomea'' || [[Flappet lark]]   || Central Africa\n|-\n| [[File:Mirafra angolensis, Tembe, Birding Weto, a.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra angolensis'' ||[[Angolan lark]]   || southern and central Africa\n|-\n| || ''Mirafra williamsi'' || [[Williams's lark]]    || northern Kenya\n|-\n| [[File:Mirafra passerina.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra passerina'' || [[Monotonous lark]]  ||  southern Africa. \n|-\n| || ''Mirafra cheniana'' || [[Melodious lark]]   || South Africa (Eastern Cape, the Free State, Gauteng, KwaZulu-Natal, Limpopo, and North West Province), Botswana and Zimbabwe\n|-\n| [[File:Horsfield's Bushlark (Mirafra javanica) (12100175043) (cropped).jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra javanica'' || [[Horsfield's bush lark]]  || Australia and much of Southeast Asia.\n|-\n| [[File:Singing Bushlark (35788711384).jpg|120px]]||''Mirafra cantillans'' || [[Singing bush lark]]  || Africa, the Middle East, and South Asia\n|-\n| [[File:Burmese bush lark (34709480896).jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra microptera'' ||  [[Burmese bush lark]]   || central Myanmar\n|-\n| [[File:Bengal bushlark (Mirafra assamica) in Kolkata W IMG 4596.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra assamica'' || [[Bengal bush lark]]   || Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Myanmar and Nepal\n|-\n| [[File:Indochinese Bushlark - Thailand S4E5419 (16760003590) (cropped).jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra erythrocephala'' || [[Indochinese bush lark]]    || southeast Asia. \n|-\n| [[File:Indian Bushlark at Rajkot.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra erythroptera'' || [[Indian bush lark]]   ||  Pakistan and northwestern, central and south-central India. \n|-\n| [[File:Jerdon's Bushlark Mirafra affinis Sri Lanka by Dr. Raju Kasambe DSCN3839 (3).jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra affinis'' ||[[Jerdon's bush lark]]   || southeast India and Sri Lanka\n|-\n| || ''Mirafra gilletti'' || [[Gillett's lark]]  || Ethiopia, Kenya, and Somalia\n|-\n| || ''Mirafra rufa'' || [[Rusty bush lark]]  ||  Sahel region of north-central Africa.\n|-\n| [[File:Collared Lark.jpg|120px]]||''Mirafra collaris'' || [[Collared lark]]  ||  eastern Ethiopia and Somalia to central Kenya\n|-\n| || ''Mirafra ashi'' || [[Ash's lark]]  || Somalia. \n|-\n| || ''Mirafra somalica'' || [[Somali lark]]  || Somalia\n|-\n||| ''Mirafra pulpa''|| [[Friedmann's lark]]  || East Africa. \n|-\n| || ''Mirafra cordofanica'' || [[Kordofan lark]]   || Mauritania and Senegal to Niger, eastern Chad, southern Sudan and northern South Sudan\n|-\n| || ''Mirafra albicauda'' || [[White-tailed lark]]  || western Chad, eastern Sudan, northeastern South Sudan, south-central Ethiopia, and from Uganda and western Kenya to central Tanzania\n|-\n|}\n\n===Former species===\nSome authorities, either presently or formerly, recognize several additional species as belonging to the genus ''Mirafra'', including:\n* [[Short-clawed lark]] (as ''Mirafra chuana'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=3244C2049F4C836E|title=Certhilauda chuana - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n* [[Dusky lark]] (as ''Mirafra nigricans'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=511C1E5A797CBD71|title=Pinarocorys nigricans - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n* [[Rufous-rumped lark]] (as ''Mirafra erythropygia'' or ''Mirafra nigricans erythropygia'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=148AA19260BD531C|title=Pinarocorys erythropygia - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n* [[Indian desert finch-lark]] (as ''Mirafra phoenicuroides'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=83362BA4&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Ammomanes deserti phoenicuroides - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-12-16}}</ref>\n* [[Rufous-tailed lark]] (as ''Mirafra phoenicura'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=0E1F8A50C06E1D74|title=Ammomanes phoenicura - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-12-17}}</ref>\n* [[Madagascan lark]] (as ''Mirafra hova'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=E6FDE8D947687594|title=Eremopterix hova - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-14}}</ref>\n* [[Sabota lark]] (as ''Mirafra sabota'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=516A194976B45CE3|title=Calendulauda sabota - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref>\n* [[Bradfield's lark]] (as ''Mirafra naevia'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=E6977C8C&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Calendulauda naevia - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref>\n* [[Pink-breasted lark]] (as ''Mirafra poecilosterna'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=99F447ADD9E4A9C7|title=Calendulauda poecilosterna - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref>\n* [[Foxy lark]] (as ''Mirafra alopex'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=CF87044518A23DE7|title=Calendulauda alopex - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref>\n* [[Masai fawn-coloured lark]] (as ''Mirafra intercedens'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=6603FDFF980831C3|title=Calendulauda intercedens - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref>\n* [[Fawn-coloured lark]] (as ''Mirafra africanoides'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=B14CE06F&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Calendulauda africanoides - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref>\n* [[Karoo lark]] (as ''Mirafra albescens'' or ''Mirafra nivosa'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=DD338581&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Calendulauda albescens - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref>\n* [[Red lark]] (as ''Mirafra burra'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=E591A2D70E920429|title=Calendulauda burra - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref>\n* [[Dune lark]] (as ''Mirafra erythrochlamys'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=214FC4649C27757F|title=Calendulauda erythrochlamys - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref>\n* [[Barlow's lark]] (as ''Mirafra erythrochlamys barlowi'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=6B1A9EF8&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Calendulauda barlowi - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref>\n* [[Rudd's lark]] (as ''Mirafra ruddi'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=2B8E5C63&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Heteromirafra ruddi - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-21}}</ref>\n* [[Archer's lark]] (as ''Mirafra archeri'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=CF0FECC361144AD3|title=Heteromirafra archeri - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-21}}</ref>\n* [[Sidamo lark]] (as ''Mirafra sidamoensis'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=A06BC1E6&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Heteromirafra sidamoensis - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-21}}</ref>\n* [[Ngaundere sun lark]] (as ''Mirafra str\u00fcmpelli'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=9C6260B5&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Galerida modesta struempelli - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-12-06}}</ref>\n* [[Uele sun lark]] (as ''Mirafra bucolica'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=27116673&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Galerida modesta bucolica - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-12-06}}</ref>\n\n{{Commons category}}\n<!-- Forktail13:97. -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q240083}}\n\n[[Category:Alaudidae]]\n[[Category:Bird genera]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Alaudidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Automatic Taxobox\n| image = Bengal bushlark (Mirafra assamica) in Kolkata W IMG 4596.jpg\n| image_caption =  [[Bengal bush lark]] (''Mirafra assamica'')<br/>in [[Kolkata]] ([[West Bengal]], India) \n| taxon = Mirafra\n| authority = [[Thomas Horsfield|Horsfield]], 1821\n| diversity_link = #Species list in taxonomic order\n| diversity = 24 species <small>(but see text)</small>\n| synonyms = * ''Geocoraphus''\n* ''Megalophonus''\n* ''Spilocorydon''\n| range_map = Mirafra distribution map.png\n| range_map_caption = {{legend0|#008000|global range of genus|outline=gray}}<ref name = map>Based on maps in the Handbook of the Birds of the World and the BirdLife Datazone</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Mirafra''''' is a genus of [[lark]] in the [[Alaudidae]] family. Some ''Mirafra'' species are called \"larks\", while others are called \"bush larks\". They are found from Africa through South Asia to Australia.\n\n==Taxonomy and systematics==\nThe phylogeny of larks (Alaudidae) was reviewed by Alstr\u00f6m et al. (2013) who found that the following species form a well supported monophyletic group, which is the sister lineage to [[Heteromirafra]].<ref name=\"Alstr\u00f6m et al. (2013)\">{{cite journal|last1=Alstr\u00f6m|first1=Per|last2=Barnes|first2=Keith N.|last3=Olsson|first3=Urban|last4=Barker|first4=F. Keith|last5=Bloomer|first5=Paulette|last6=Khan|first6=Aleem Ahmed|last7=Qureshi|first7=Masood Ahmed|last8=Guillaumet|first8=Alban|last9=Crochet|first9=Pierre-Andre|last10=Ryan|first10=Peter G.|title=Multilocus phylogeny of the avian family Alaudidae (larks) reveals complex morphological evolution, non-monophyletic genera and hidden species diversity|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|date=2013|volume=69|issue=3|pages=1043\u20131056|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2013.06.005|pmid=23792153|url=https://pub.epsilon.slu.se/11222/2/alstrom_fig_1.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Extant species===\nThe genus contains twenty-four species:<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2018 | title=Nicators, reedling, larks | work=World Bird List Version 8.2 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/larks/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=15 July 2018 }}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Image !! Scientific name !! Common Name !! Distribution\n|-\n| [[File:Eastern clapper lark (Mirafra fasciolata subsp fasciolata), crop.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra fasciolata''|| [[Eastern clapper lark]]   || southern Africa in Zambia, Namibia, Botswana, Lesotho and South Africa.\n|-\n| [[File:Mirafra apiata -Namaqua National Park, South Africa-8 Cropped.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra apiata'' || [[Cape clapper lark]]  || southern Africa\n|-\n| [[File:Red-winged Lark.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra hypermetra'' || [[Red-winged lark]]   || Ethiopia, Kenya, Somalia, South Sudan, Tanzania and Uganda\n|-\n| [[File:Mirafra africana2.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra africana'' || [[Rufous-naped lark]]  ||  sub-Saharan Africa\n|-\n| [[File:Flappet Lark, Sakania, DR Congo (16025285505), crop.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra rufocinnamomea'' || [[Flappet lark]]   || Central Africa\n|-\n| [[File:Mirafra angolensis, Tembe, Birding Weto, a.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra angolensis'' ||[[Angolan lark]]   || southern and central Africa\n|-\n| || ''Mirafra williamsi'' || [[Williams's lark]]    || northern Kenya\n|-\n| [[File:Mirafra passerina.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra passerina'' || [[Monotonous lark]]  ||  southern Africa. \n|-\n| || ''Mirafra cheniana'' || [[Melodious lark]]   || South Africa (Eastern Cape, the Free State, Gauteng, KwaZulu-Natal, Limpopo, and North West Province), Botswana and Zimbabwe\n|-\n| [[File:Horsfield's Bushlark (Mirafra javanica) (12100175043) (cropped).jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra javanica'' || [[Horsfield's bush lark]]  || Australia and much of Southeast Asia.\n|-\n| [[File:Singing Bushlark (35788711384).jpg|120px]]||''Mirafra cantillans'' || [[Singing bush lark]]  || Africa, the Middle East, and South Asia\n|-\n| [[File:Burmese bush lark (34709480896).jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra microptera'' ||  [[Burmese bush lark]]   || central Myanmar\n|-\n| [[File:Bengal bushlark (Mirafra assamica) in Kolkata W IMG 4596.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra assamica'' || [[Bengal bush lark]]   || Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Myanmar and Nepal\n|-\n| [[File:Indochinese Bushlark - Thailand S4E5419 (16760003590) (cropped).jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra erythrocephala'' || [[Indochinese bush lark]]    || southeast Asia. \n|-\n| [[File:Indian Bushlark at Rajkot.jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra erythroptera'' || [[Indian bush lark]]   ||  Pakistan and north-western, central and south-central India. \n|-\n| [[File:Jerdon's Bushlark Mirafra affinis Sri Lanka by Dr. Raju Kasambe DSCN3839 (3).jpg|120px]]|| ''Mirafra affinis'' ||[[Jerdon's bush lark]]   || south-east India and Sri Lanka\n|-\n| || ''Mirafra gilletti'' || [[Gillett's lark]]  || Ethiopia, Kenya, and Somalia\n|-\n| || ''Mirafra rufa'' || [[Rusty bush lark]]  ||  Sahel region of north-central Africa.\n|-\n| [[File:Collared Lark.jpg|120px]]||''Mirafra collaris'' || [[Collared lark]]  ||  eastern Ethiopia and Somalia to central Kenya\n|-\n| || ''Mirafra ashi'' || [[Ash's lark]]  || Somalia. \n|-\n| || ''Mirafra somalica'' || [[Somali lark]]  || Somalia\n|-\n||| ''Mirafra pulpa''|| [[Friedmann's lark]]  || East Africa. \n|-\n| || ''Mirafra cordofanica'' || [[Kordofan lark]]   || Mauritania and Senegal to Niger, eastern Chad, southern Sudan and northern South Sudan\n|-\n| || ''Mirafra albicauda'' || [[White-tailed lark]]  || western Chad, eastern Sudan, north-eastern South Sudan, south-central Ethiopia, and from Uganda and western Kenya to central Tanzania\n|-\n|}\n\n===Former species===\nSome authorities, either presently or formerly, recognize several additional species as belonging to the genus ''Mirafra'' including:\n* [[Short-clawed lark]] (as ''Mirafra chuana'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=3244C2049F4C836E|title=Certhilauda chuana - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n* [[Dusky lark]] (as ''Mirafra nigricans'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=511C1E5A797CBD71|title=Pinarocorys nigricans - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n* [[Rufous-rumped lark]] (as ''Mirafra erythropygia'' or ''Mirafra nigricans erythropygia'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=148AA19260BD531C|title=Pinarocorys erythropygia - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n* [[Indian desert finch-lark]] (as ''Mirafra phoenicuroides'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=83362BA4&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Ammomanes deserti phoenicuroides - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-12-16}}</ref>\n* [[Rufous-tailed lark]] (as ''Mirafra phoenicura'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=0E1F8A50C06E1D74|title=Ammomanes phoenicura - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-12-17}}</ref>\n* [[Madagascan lark]] (as ''Mirafra hova'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=E6FDE8D947687594|title=Eremopterix hova - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-14}}</ref>\n* [[Sabota lark]] (as ''Mirafra sabota'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=516A194976B45CE3|title=Calendulauda sabota - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref>\n* [[Bradfield's lark]] (as ''Mirafra naevia'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=E6977C8C&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Calendulauda naevia - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref>\n* [[Pink-breasted lark]] (as ''Mirafra poecilosterna'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=99F447ADD9E4A9C7|title=Calendulauda poecilosterna - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref>\n* [[Foxy lark]] (as ''Mirafra alopex'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=CF87044518A23DE7|title=Calendulauda alopex - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref>\n* [[Masai fawn-coloured lark]] (as ''Mirafra intercedens'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=6603FDFF980831C3|title=Calendulauda intercedens - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref>\n* [[Fawn-coloured lark]] (as ''Mirafra africanoides'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=B14CE06F&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Calendulauda africanoides - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref>\n* [[Karoo lark]] (as ''Mirafra albescens'' or ''Mirafra nivosa'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=DD338581&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Calendulauda albescens - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref>\n* [[Red lark]] (as ''Mirafra burra'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=E591A2D70E920429|title=Calendulauda burra - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref>\n* [[Dune lark]] (as ''Mirafra erythrochlamys'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=214FC4649C27757F|title=Calendulauda erythrochlamys - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref>\n* [[Barlow's lark]] (as ''Mirafra erythrochlamys barlowi'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=6B1A9EF8&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Calendulauda barlowi - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-19}}</ref>\n* [[Rudd's lark]] (as ''Mirafra ruddi'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=2B8E5C63&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Heteromirafra ruddi - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-21}}</ref>\n* [[Archer's lark]] (as ''Mirafra archeri'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=CF0FECC361144AD3|title=Heteromirafra archeri - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-21}}</ref>\n* [[Sidamo lark]] (as ''Mirafra sidamoensis'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=A06BC1E6&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Heteromirafra sidamoensis - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-11-21}}</ref>\n* [[Ngaundere sun lark]] (as ''Mirafra str\u00fcmpelli'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=9C6260B5&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Galerida modesta struempelli - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-12-06}}</ref>\n* [[Uele sun lark]] (as ''Mirafra bucolica'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=27116673&sec=summary&ssver=1|title=Galerida modesta bucolica - Avibase|website=avibase.bsc-eoc.org|access-date=2016-12-06}}</ref>\n\n{{Commons category}}\n<!-- Forktail13:97. -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q240083}}\n\n[[Category:Alaudidae]]\n[[Category:Bird genera]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Alaudidae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirafra"}
